{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.27,0.31,0.3,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85543"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4093"},{"type":"tags","id":"11116"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46072"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of worsening dysmenorrhoea, deep dyspareunia, and chronic pelvic pain. She has been trying to conceive for 18 months without success. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports her symptoms are significantly impacting her quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Bimanual examination reveals a \u003Cstrong\u003Er\u003C/strong\u003Eetroverted uterus with mild tenderness in the posterior fornix. A transvaginal ultrasound demonstrates a right ovarian cyst with a ground glass appearance measuring 3.5 cm. The left ovary appears normal. She is referred to a gynaecologist for consideration of laparoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best pre-surgical estimate of endometriosis stage and category in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stage I, Category 1","Stage II, Category 2","Stage II, Category 3","Stage III-IV, Category 2","Stage III-IV, Category 4"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hallmark features of endometriosis, including cyclical pelvic pain, dyspareunia, and an ultrasound-confirmed ovarian endometrioma measuring \u0026gt;3 cm. These findings are consistent with ovarian endometriosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe revised American Society for Reproductive Medicine (rASRM) Staging System is used to classify endometriosis based on lesion size, depth, location, and the presence of adhesions. It includes four stages:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage I (Minimal): Few superficial implants, no significant adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage II (Mild): More and deeper implants, still minimal adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage III (Moderate):\u003C/strong\u003E Presence of endometriomas and some adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IV (Severe):\u003C/strong\u003E Large endometriomas, dense adhesions, and extensive involvement of pelvic structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the presence of a \u0026gt;3 cm ovarian endometrioma, moderate (Stage III) or severe (Stage IV) disease is likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndometriosis is also commonly classified into three categories: superficial peritoneal disease (category 1), ovarian endometriosis \u003Cstrong\u003E(category 2)\u003C/strong\u003E and deep infiltrating endometriosis (DIE), defined as endometriotic lesions invading \u0026gt;5\u00a0mm beyond the surface of the peritoneum (category 3). There is no category 4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted that imaging cannot definitively confirm adhesions or deep involvement, so both stages III and IV remain possible until laparoscopy is performed. Predicting likely endometriosis stage is important for preoperative surgical planning including considerations of where is most appropriate for surgery (e.g. general gynaecology, specialised endometriosis surgeon, colorectal surgeon if bowel endometriosis is suspected), how long to allocate for operating time and additional investigations that might be ordered before laparoscopy (e.g. MRI).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement options include hormonal suppression and/or laparoscopic surgery, depending on the patient\u0027s symptoms and fertility desires. Given this patient\u0027s desire for pregnancy and the presence of bilateral endometriomas, referral for surgical management would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometriomas \u003E3 cm on transvaginal ultrasound are highly suggestive of stage III or IV endometriosis.","Predicting likely endometriosis stage by imaging prior to laparoscopy is important for preoperative surgical planning."],"references":["Crump J, Suker A. Endometriosis: A review of recent evidence and guidelines. Aust J Gen Pract. 2024;53(1\u20132):23\u201329. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/january-february/endometriosis","Lee SY, Koo YJ, Lee DH. Classification of endometriosis. Yeungnam Univ J Med. 2021 Jan;38(1):10-18. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2020.00444. Epub 2020 Aug 7. PMID: 32764213; PMCID: PMC7787892.","Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Endometriosis: Clinical Practice Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Endometriosis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf","Tsamantioti ES, Mahdy H. Endometriosis. [Updated 2023 Jan 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-19T08:51:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T08:52:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://ap